You are given an array of N integers, A1, A2 ,â€¦, AN. Return maximum value of f(i, j) for all 1 â‰¤ i, j â‰¤ N.
f(i, j) is defined as |A[i] - A[j]| + |i - j|, where |x| denotes absolute value of x.

For example,

A=[1, 3, -1]

f(1, 1) = f(2, 2) = f(3, 3) = 0
f(1, 2) = f(2, 1) = |1 - 3| + |1 - 2| = 3
f(1, 3) = f(3, 1) = |1 - (-1)| + |1 - 3| = 4
f(2, 3) = f(3, 2) = |3 - (-1)| + |2 - 3| = 5

So, we return 5.


Solution:
Manhattan distance between 2 points (x1,y1) and (x2,y2) are given as:
|x1-x2| + |y1-y2|

Let x1>x2 and y1>y2
max(|x1-x2|+|y1-y2|) = max(x1-x2+y1-y2) = max(x1+y1) - min(x2+y2)

Let  x1>x2 and y1<y2
max(|x1-x2|+|y1-y2|) = max(x1-x2-y1+y2) = max(x1-y1) - min(x2-y2)

Now change x1 with x2 and you take the same results.

Result:
max ( (max(xi+yi)-min(xi+yi)), (max(xi-yi) - min(xi-yi)) ) 
